<HEADLINE>
Clashes, airstrikes leave 21 Taliban dead in Afghanistan
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KABUL, Afghanistan 2007-04-29 00:02:56 UTC
</P>
<P>
At least 21 insurgents were killed as Afghan and coalition forces
clashed with Taliban militants in separate incidents in the east
and south, officials said.
</P>
<P>
The police and Taliban engaged in an hour-long gunbattle in Khost
province's Alishar district Saturday, said Wazir Padshah, a
spokesman for the provincial police. He said NATO assisted with
an airstrike, killing 11 militants. Three police were also
wounded.
</P>
<P>
Lt. Col. Angela Billings, spokeswoman for NATO's International
Security Assistance Force or ISAF, confirmed that NATO launched
an airstrike early Saturday, causing some insurgent casualties.
She said there were no NATO or civilian casualties.
</P>
<P>
The latest violence came as NATO-led forces pushed forward with
their largest-ever operation in southern Afghanistan to root out
militants in Helmand province's opium-producing heartland.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday in Helmand, Afghan and coalition forces killed 10
suspected Taliban in a clash and airstrike, the coalition said in
a statement.
</P>
<P>
Coalition forces engaged in a ground battle after their convoy
was ambushed by the Taliban near Gereshk district. A subsequent
airstrike destroyed two buildings from which the militants were
firing, the statement said. There were no coalition casualties.
</P>
<P>
Separately, a NATO service member was found dead in his barracks
Friday afternoon, said an ISAF statement issued from Bagram Air
Base, north of Kabul. The statement, issued Saturday, did not
give any further details and said the cause of death was under
investigation.
</P>
<P>
In eastern Afghanistan, another NATO soldier died and one was
injured on Saturday, said a separate ISAF statement. It said the
death and injury were from non-combat related causes, but did not
give any further details.
</P>
